proof.p:
To justify the first equality, we need to show that a vector x is perpendicular to all of the vectors in W if and only if it is perpendicular to v_1,v_2,\ldots,v_m. Since the v_i are contained in W, we really only have to show that if x\cdot v_1 = x\cdot v_2 = \cdots = x\cdot v_m = 0, then x is perpendicular to every vector v in W. Indeed, any vector in W has the form v = c_1v_1 + c_2v_2 + \cdots + c_mv_m for suitable scalars c_1,c_2,\ldots,c_m, so
\begin{split} x\cdot v \amp= x\cdot(c_1v_1 + c_2v_2 + \cdots + c_mv_m) \\ \amp= c_1(x\cdot v_1) + c_2(x\cdot v_2) + \cdots + c_m(x\cdot v_m) \\ \amp= c_1(0) + c_2(0) + \cdots + c_m(0) = 0. \end{split}
Therefore, x is in W^\perp.

To prove the second equality, we let

  A = \mat{
    \matrow{v_1^T};
    \matrow{v_2^T};
    \vdots;
    \matrow{v_m^T}}.

By the row-column rule for matrix multiplication, for any vector x in \R^n we have

  Ax = \vec{v_1^Tx v_2^Tx \vdots, v_m^Tx}
  = \vec{v_1\cdot x v_2\cdot x \vdots, v_m\cdot x}.

Therefore, x is in \Nul(A) if and only if x is perpendicular to each vector v_1,v_2,\ldots,v_m.

subsection.p:
Orthogonal complementof a span
Spanorthogonal complement of
    Since column spaces are the same as spans, we can rephrase the proposition as follows.  Let v_1,v_2,\ldots,v_m be vectors in \R^n, and let W = \Span\{v_1,v_2,\ldots,v_m\}.  Then

      W^\perp =
      \bigl\{\text{all vectors orthogonal to each $v_1,v_2,\ldots,v_m$}\bigr\}
      = \Nul\mat{
      \matrow{v_1^T};
      \matrow{v_2^T};
      \vdots;
      \matrow{v_m^T}}.

Again, it is important to be able to go easily back and forth between spans and column spaces.  If you are handed a span, you can apply the proposition once you have rewritten your span as a column space.

Orthogonal complementsystem of linear equations By the proposition, computing the orthogonal complement of a span means solving a system of linear equations. For example, if
v_1 = \vec{1 7 2} \qquad v_2 = \vec{-2 3 1}
then \Span\{v_1,v_2\}^\perp is the solution set of the homogeneous linear system associated to the matrix
\mat{\matrow{v_1^T}; \matrow{v_2^T}} = \mat{1 7 2; -2 3 1}.
This is the solution set of the system of equations
\syseq{x_1 + 7x_2 + 2x_3 = 0; -2x_1 + 3x_2 + x_3 = 0\rlap.}

proof.p:
It follows from the previous paragraph that k \leq n.  Suppose that k \lt n.  Then the matrix

  A = \mat{
    \matrow{v_1^T};
    \matrow{v_2^T};
    \vdots;
    \matrow{v_k^T}}

has more columns than rows (it is wide), so its null space is nonzero by this .  Let x be a nonzero vector in \Nul(A).  Then

  0 = Ax = \vec{v_1^Tx v_2^Tx \vdots, v_k^Tx}
  = \vec{v_1\cdot x v_2\cdot x \vdots, v_k\cdot x}

by the row-column rule for matrix multiplication.  Since v_1\cdot x = v_2\cdot x = \cdots = v_m\cdot x = 0, it follows from this  that x is in W^\perp, and similarly, x is in (W^\perp)^\perp.  As above, this implies x is orthogonal to itself, which contradicts our assumption that x is nonzero.  Therefore, k = n, as desired.

subsection.p:
See these  for pictures of the second property.  As for the third: for example, if W is a (2-dimensional) plane in \R^4, then W^\perp is another (2-dimensional) plane.  Explicitly, we have

  \begin{split}
  \Span\bigl\{e_1,e_2\bigr\}^\perp
  \amp= \left\{\vec{x y z w}\text{ in }\R^4\biggm|\vec{x y z w}\cdot\vec{1 0 0 0} = 0 \text{ and } \vec{x y z w}\vec{0 1 0 0} = 0\right\} \\
  \amp= \left\{\vec{0 0 z w}\text{ in }\R^4\right\}
  = \Span\bigl\{e_3,e_4\}:
  \end{split}

the orthogonal complement of the xy-plane is the zw-plane.

bluebox.p:
For any vectors v_1,v_2,\ldots,v_m, we have

  \Span\{v_1,v_2,\ldots,v_m\}^\perp = \Nul\mat{
    \matrow{v_1^T};
    \matrow{v_2^T};
    \vdots;
    \matrow{v_m^T}}.

For any matrix A, we have

  \begin{aligned}
    \Row(A)^\perp &= \Nul(A)    &  \Nul(A)^\perp &= \Row(A) \\
    \Col(A)^\perp &= \Nul(A^T)\quad  &  \Nul(A^T)^\perp &= \Col(A).
  \end{aligned}
